<div class="section-divider" id="section-1">
  <div class="eyebrow">Section 1</div>
  <h2>Identifying Vessels in Tissue</h2>
  <p class="sub">How to recognize arteries, veins, and accompanying nerves in cross-section by their distinctive appearances.</p>
</div>
<main>
<article class="plate" id="plate-01">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 01</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Artery, Vein, and Nerve in Cross-Section</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The classic neurovascular bundle: an artery, vein, and nerve traveling together. Each has a distinctive appearance under H&E staining that lets you identify it at a glance.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Artery, Vein, and Nerve in Cross-Section" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Round, open lumen with a thick muscular wall. The wall has prominent concentric layers of smooth muscle with elastic fibers. Holds its shape after death because of the muscle tone in the wall.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Irregular, often collapsed lumen with a much thinner wall. Wall layers are less distinct than artery, and the lumen tends to be larger relative to wall thickness. May contain valves in cross-section.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Nerve (Fascicle)</div><div class="id-card-text">Pale, fibrillar appearance with no lumen. Nerve fibers run longitudinally and appear as fine wavy lines or dots depending on the section angle. Surrounded by pinker connective tissue (epineurium).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Neurovascular Bundle</div><div class="id-card-text">The grouping of artery, vein, and nerve traveling together through tissue. Surgical landmarks rely on this consistent triad.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">The Neurovascular Bundle in Procedures</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Knowing the artery-vein-nerve relationship matters for every IV start, arterial line placement, and regional nerve block. The femoral neurovascular bundle is the textbook example: from lateral to medial it goes Nerve, Artery, Vein, Empty space (NAVEL). Aspirate before injecting any local anesthetic to avoid intravascular delivery; if a nerve is too close to the vessel, hitting it produces paresthesia and signals you to redirect.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-02">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 02</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Artery and Vein Side by Side</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">A higher-power view of the artery shows the thick tunica media, with the wavy internal elastic lamina forming the boundary between media and the lumen. The neighboring vein has a much thinner wall.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Artery and Vein Side by Side" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Artery (Cross Section)</div><div class="id-card-text">Round vessel with thick wall. The lumen is small relative to wall thickness, the opposite ratio from a vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Media of Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">The middle and thickest layer. Contains circumferential smooth muscle that contracts (vasoconstriction) or relaxes (vasodilation) to regulate blood pressure and distribute flow.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Externa of Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">The outermost connective tissue layer. Contains collagen, fibroblasts, and the vasa vasorum (small vessels that supply the wall of large vessels).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Internal Elastic Lamina</div><div class="id-card-text">The wavy darkly-stained line at the inner edge of the tunica media. Appears scalloped because the vessel was cut during fixation and the elastic recoil produced these characteristic folds.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Vein (Adjacent)</div><div class="id-card-text">Larger but thinner-walled vessel near the artery. Wall layers are far less distinct than the artery; tunica media is sparse and the wall is dominated by tunica externa.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Distinguishing Arterial from Venous Bleeding</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">The same wall differences seen on histology explain how clinicians distinguish bleeding type at the bedside. Arterial bleeding is bright red (oxygenated) and pulsatile because the muscular artery wall recoils after each ventricular contraction. Venous bleeding is dark red (deoxygenated) and steady because veins lack the muscular recoil. Arterial bleeding requires direct pressure and possibly a tourniquet; venous bleeding usually responds to pressure and elevation alone.</div>
</div>
</article>
</main>
<div class="section-divider" id="section-2">
  <div class="eyebrow">Section 2</div>
  <h2>Vessel Wall Architecture by Size</h2>
  <p class="sub">How vessel walls change as you move from large arteries through smaller arterioles down to the venous side.</p>
</div>
<main>
<article class="plate" id="plate-03">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 03</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Large Muscular Artery</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">A view of the wall of a large artery. Note the multiple wavy bands of darkly-stained elastic tissue running through the wall. The inner boundary is marked by the prominent internal elastic lamina.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Large Muscular Artery" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Media</div><div class="id-card-text">The thick middle layer dominating the wall. Contains smooth muscle and abundant elastic fibers organized in concentric layers (elastic lamellae).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Externa</div><div class="id-card-text">Outermost layer of connective tissue. Less organized than the media; contains collagen, fibroblasts, and the vasa vasorum that supplies the outer wall layers.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Internal Elastic Lamina</div><div class="id-card-text">The single most prominent wavy elastic band, marking the boundary between tunica intima (not visible at this magnification) and tunica media. Recoils after fixation, creating the scalloped appearance.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Elastic Lamellae</div><div class="id-card-text">Multiple concentric sheets of elastin within the tunica media. Allow the vessel to expand during systole and recoil during diastole, smoothing pulsatile flow into more continuous flow downstream.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Aortic Dissection</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">When the elastic lamellae of the aorta tear, blood enters the wall itself and propagates between the layers, creating a false lumen. This is aortic dissection: a true emergency with sudden tearing chest or back pain. The Stanford classification splits dissections into Type A (involves the ascending aorta, surgical emergency, mortality 1 percent per hour untreated) and Type B (descending only, often medically managed). Risk factors include hypertension, connective tissue disorders (Marfan, Ehlers-Danlos), and bicuspid aortic valve.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-04">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 04</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Small Muscular Artery</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">A complete cross-section of a small muscular artery showing all three tunicae. Compared to a large artery, the wall is dominated by smooth muscle rather than elastic tissue.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Small Muscular Artery" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Intima</div><div class="id-card-text">Innermost layer. Consists of a single layer of endothelial cells resting on a thin basement membrane and a small amount of subendothelial connective tissue, bounded externally by the internal elastic lamina.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Media</div><div class="id-card-text">Middle and thickest layer in muscular arteries. Composed almost entirely of circumferentially arranged smooth muscle. Contraction narrows the lumen (vasoconstriction); relaxation widens it (vasodilation).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Externa</div><div class="id-card-text">Outer layer of connective tissue. Contains collagen, elastic fibers, fibroblasts, and small nutritive vessels (vasa vasorum) for the outer wall.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Internal Elastic Lamina</div><div class="id-card-text">Wavy darkly-stained band at the intima-media boundary. More prominent in muscular arteries than veins; provides a useful identification feature.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Where Atherosclerosis Strikes</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Atherosclerotic plaques form preferentially at branch points and curvatures of muscular arteries (coronaries, carotids, femorals, renals) where blood flow becomes turbulent. The plaque begins in the tunica intima with LDL deposition and macrophage uptake (foam cells), then grows with smooth muscle proliferation and a fibrous cap. Plaque rupture exposes the thrombogenic core to blood, triggering acute thrombosis: a coronary plaque that ruptures becomes a heart attack; a carotid plaque rupture becomes a stroke.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-05">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 05</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Arterioles</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The smallest arteries before capillaries. Multiple cross-sections show the characteristic appearance: a tiny lumen with red blood cells, surrounded by one or two layers of smooth muscle.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Arterioles" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Arteriole</div><div class="id-card-text">Smallest arterial vessel before reaching capillary level. Diameter usually under 100 micrometers. Wall typically has only one to two layers of smooth muscle in the tunica media.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Lumen with RBCs</div><div class="id-card-text">Red blood cells (eosinophilic, biconcave discs) sit inside the lumen. Their presence inside a small thick-walled vessel confirms it is an arteriole rather than a venule of similar size.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Media (Reduced)</div><div class="id-card-text">In an arteriole, the media is reduced to one or two layers of smooth muscle cells visible as flattened nuclei wrapping the lumen.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Externa (Sparse)</div><div class="id-card-text">Almost absent at this level; just a wisp of connective tissue around the muscle layer.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Arterioles and Blood Pressure</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Arterioles are the resistance vessels of the circulation: their constriction or dilation accounts for most of the systemic vascular resistance that determines diastolic blood pressure. Chronic hypertension thickens the arteriolar wall (hyaline arteriolosclerosis from protein deposition, or hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis with concentric "onion-skinning" in malignant hypertension), narrowing the lumen and damaging end organs (kidney, retina, brain). Most antihypertensive drugs work at this level.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-06">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 06</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Vein</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">A vein in longitudinal section, with a comparison cross-section of a small artery showing all three tunicae for contrast. Note how the vein wall is thin, irregular, and lacks the prominent internal elastic lamina that defines arteries.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Vein" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Vein Wall (Thin)</div><div class="id-card-text">Thin, irregular wall with poorly defined layers. Tunica media is sparse with little smooth muscle. Tunica externa is the thickest layer in larger veins, dominated by collagen.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Vein Lumen</div><div class="id-card-text">Large relative to wall thickness, often collapsed in fixed tissue (the "lumen-to-wall" ratio is the easiest way to distinguish veins from arteries on a slide).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Comparison Artery (Inset)</div><div class="id-card-text">A small artery shown in the inset for direct comparison. The artery has a prominent wavy internal elastic lamina and a thick tunica media dominated by smooth muscle, both absent in the adjacent vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Intima of Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Innermost layer of the inset artery. Endothelium plus thin connective tissue, bounded by the wavy internal elastic lamina.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Media of Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Middle layer of the inset artery. Concentric smooth muscle, much thicker than anything seen in the adjacent vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Tunica Externa of Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Outer connective tissue layer of the inset artery.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Varicose Veins and Venous Insufficiency</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Veins below the heart depend on three mechanisms to push blood upward: skeletal muscle pump, respiratory pump, and one-way valves at intervals along the vein. When valve leaflets become incompetent (often from prolonged standing, pregnancy, or genetic predisposition), blood pools and stretches the wall further, propagating the failure to the next valve down. The result is varicose veins (dilated, tortuous superficial veins of the legs) and chronic venous insufficiency (stasis dermatitis, hyperpigmentation, ulceration over the medial malleolus).</div>
</div>
</article>
</main>
<div class="section-divider" id="section-3">
  <div class="eyebrow">Section 3</div>
  <h2>Arteries of the Head, Neck, and Upper Extremity</h2>
  <p class="sub">The arterial tree from the aortic arch up into the head and neck and out to the fingertips.</p>
</div>
<main>
<article class="plate" id="plate-07">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 07</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Arteries of the Head and Neck</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The arterial supply to the head and neck originates from the aortic arch. On the right, the brachiocephalic trunk splits into the right common carotid and right subclavian. On the left, the common carotid and subclavian arise directly from the arch.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Arteries of the Head and Neck" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Ascending Aorta</div><div class="id-card-text">First segment of the aorta arising from the left ventricle. Gives off the coronary arteries before continuing as the aortic arch.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Aortic Arch</div><div class="id-card-text">Curves over the pulmonary trunk and left main bronchus. Gives off three major branches in order: brachiocephalic trunk, left common carotid, left subclavian.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Brachiocephalic Trunk</div><div class="id-card-text">First branch of the aortic arch. Short artery (about 4 to 5 cm) that divides behind the right sternoclavicular joint into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Right Common Carotid Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Branch of the brachiocephalic trunk. Ascends in the neck without branching until it bifurcates into internal and external carotid arteries at the level of C4 (upper border of thyroid cartilage).</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Left Common Carotid Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Second branch of the aortic arch (arises directly, no brachiocephalic on the left). Same course as the right after entering the neck.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Right Subclavian Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Branch of the brachiocephalic trunk. Passes posterior to the clavicle and over the first rib; gives off the vertebral artery and others before becoming the axillary artery at the lateral border of the first rib.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Left Subclavian Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Third branch of the aortic arch (arises directly). Same downstream course as the right subclavian.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Left Axillary Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Continuation of the subclavian artery beyond the first rib; supplies the upper limb and shoulder region.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Facial Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Branch of the external carotid artery. Crosses the mandible at the antegonial notch (where you can palpate its pulse) to supply the face.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Carotid Bruits and Stroke Risk</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">The carotid bifurcation is a high-shear branch point and a favorite site for atherosclerotic plaque. A bruit (a whooshing sound on auscultation) over the carotid suggests turbulent flow past a stenosis. Significant carotid stenosis increases stroke risk because plaque embolizes upward to the brain. Symptomatic stenosis over 70 percent typically gets carotid endarterectomy or stenting; below 50 percent is medically managed. The classic warning is amaurosis fugax: transient monocular vision loss from an embolus to the ophthalmic artery.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-08">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 08</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Arteries of the Upper Extremity</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The arterial pathway from the chest to the fingertips: subclavian becomes axillary at the first rib, axillary becomes brachial at the lower border of teres major, and the brachial divides into radial and ulnar arteries at the elbow.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Arteries of the Upper Extremity" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Subclavian Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Origin of upper limb arterial supply. Right arises from the brachiocephalic trunk; left arises directly from the aortic arch. Becomes the axillary artery at the lateral border of the first rib.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Axillary Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Continuation of the subclavian; runs through the axilla. Supplies the shoulder region and gives branches to the chest wall. Becomes the brachial artery at the lower border of the teres major.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Brachial Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Main artery of the arm. Runs medially down the arm with the median nerve. Site of blood pressure measurement (cuff occludes here) and of the antecubital pulse. Bifurcates at the elbow into radial and ulnar arteries.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Radial Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Lateral terminal branch of the brachial artery. Runs along the radial (lateral) side of the forearm. Easily palpable at the wrist (radial pulse); the standard site for arterial line placement.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Ulnar Artery</div><div class="id-card-text">Medial and larger terminal branch of the brachial artery. Runs along the ulnar (medial) side of the forearm. Forms the dominant supply to the superficial palmar arch in most people.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">The Allen Test and Radial Arterial Lines</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Before placing a radial arterial line or harvesting the radial artery for CABG, clinicians perform the Allen test to confirm collateral flow through the ulnar artery. Compress both radial and ulnar arteries while the patient clenches the fist, release only the ulnar, and watch for palmar reperfusion within 5 to 10 seconds. A positive (slow) Allen test means inadequate ulnar collateral flow and is a relative contraindication to radial cannulation, since the hand could become ischemic if the radial occludes.</div>
</div>
</article>
</main>
<div class="section-divider" id="section-4">
  <div class="eyebrow">Section 4</div>
  <h2>Veins of the Head, Neck, and Upper Extremity</h2>
  <p class="sub">The venous return from the head, neck, and arms back to the superior vena cava and the right atrium.</p>
</div>
<main>
<article class="plate" id="plate-09">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 09</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Major Veins Returning to the Heart</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The venous return from the head, neck, and upper extremities converges into the brachiocephalic veins and then the superior vena cava. Major arteries are also visible on this view for orientation.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Major Veins Returning to the Heart" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Facial Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Drains the superficial face. Joins the internal jugular vein in the neck.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Internal Jugular Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Receives venous blood from the brain (via the dural sinuses), face, and neck. Runs in the carotid sheath alongside the common carotid artery and vagus nerve. Joins the subclavian vein behind the sternoclavicular joint to form the brachiocephalic vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Subclavian Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Continuation of the axillary vein at the lateral border of the first rib. Runs along the inferior surface of the clavicle. Receives the external jugular vein and joins the internal jugular to form the brachiocephalic vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Right Brachiocephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Formed by the union of the right internal jugular and right subclavian veins behind the right sternoclavicular joint. Joins the left brachiocephalic to form the SVC.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Superior Vena Cava (SVC)</div><div class="id-card-text">Formed by the union of the two brachiocephalic veins. Returns deoxygenated blood from the upper body to the right atrium.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Axillary Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Continuation of the basilic vein and brachial veins through the axilla. Becomes the subclavian vein at the lateral border of the first rib.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Cephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein of the lateral arm. Runs in the deltopectoral groove and pierces the clavipectoral fascia to drain into the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Brachial Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Paired deep veins accompanying the brachial artery in the arm. Drain into the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Basilic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein of the medial arm. Pierces the deep fascia about midway up the arm to become the axillary vein after joining the brachial veins.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">SVC Syndrome</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">Compression or obstruction of the superior vena cava (most often by a right-sided lung tumor or mediastinal lymphoma) blocks venous return from the upper body. The result is facial and upper-extremity swelling, distended neck and chest wall veins, headache, and sometimes stridor or dysphagia. Pemberton sign (raising both arms above the head produces facial plethora and cyanosis) is a classic provocative test. Treatment depends on cause: stenting for malignant compression, anticoagulation if catheter-related thrombus.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-10">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 10</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Jugular and Subclavian Venous System</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">Two views of the venous network draining the head, neck, and upper extremity into the brachiocephalic vein. The internal jugular runs deep alongside the carotid; the external jugular runs superficially across the sternocleidomastoid; the subclavian runs behind the clavicle.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image-multi"><figure class="multi-fig"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Left lateral view" loading="lazy"><figcaption>Left lateral view</figcaption></figure><figure class="multi-fig"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Anterior view including cephalic vein" loading="lazy"><figcaption>Anterior view including cephalic vein</figcaption></figure></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">External Jugular Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein crossing the sternocleidomastoid muscle obliquely from the angle of the mandible to the middle of the clavicle. Drains the scalp and face. Empties into the subclavian vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Internal Jugular Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Deep vein of the neck within the carotid sheath. Drains the brain (via dural sinuses), face, and neck. The right IJ provides the most direct path to the SVC and is the preferred site for central venous access.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Subclavian Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Runs along the inferior surface of the clavicle in front of the anterior scalene muscle. Continuation of the axillary vein. Joins the internal jugular to form the brachiocephalic vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Left Brachiocephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Crosses the midline behind the manubrium to join the right brachiocephalic and form the SVC. Longer than the right.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Cephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein of the lateral arm. Ends in the deltopectoral groove by piercing the clavipectoral fascia and joining the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Axillary Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Drains the upper limb. Becomes the subclavian vein at the lateral border of the first rib.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Central Venous Access: IJ vs Subclavian</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">The right internal jugular is the most popular central line site because it offers a straight shot to the SVC and tolerates ultrasound guidance well. The subclavian provides a comfortable, easy-to-secure site with the lowest infection rate but the highest pneumothorax risk (the lung apex sits just below). The left IJ is harder because it requires a sharp turn into the left brachiocephalic vein and risks injury to the thoracic duct. Trendelenburg position engorges the IJ and decreases the risk of air embolism during cannulation.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-11">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 11</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Veins of the Upper Extremity</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">The upper extremity venous drainage runs through both deep veins (paired with arteries) and superficial veins (in subcutaneous tissue). Both systems converge at the axillary vein.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Veins of the Upper Extremity" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Subclavian Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Continuation of the axillary vein at the first rib. Joins the internal jugular to form the brachiocephalic vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Axillary Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Formed by the union of the brachial veins and the basilic vein. Continuation of venous return into the chest.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Brachial Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Paired deep veins accompanying the brachial artery in the arm. Join the basilic vein in the upper arm to form the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Basilic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein of the medial forearm and arm. Pierces the deep fascia midway up the arm to join the brachial veins. The standard site for peripherally inserted central catheter (PICC) line placement.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Cephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Superficial vein of the lateral forearm and arm. Travels up the lateral arm and ends in the deltopectoral groove.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Median Cubital Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Connects the basilic and cephalic veins across the antecubital fossa. The most common site for routine venipuncture (blood draws) because it is large, superficial, and well-anchored.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Radial Vein (Deep)</div><div class="id-card-text">Paired deep veins of the forearm running with the radial artery. Join the ulnar veins to form the brachial veins.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Ulnar Vein (Deep)</div><div class="id-card-text">Paired deep veins of the forearm running with the ulnar artery. Join the radial veins to form the brachial veins.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Why Phlebotomists Aim for the Median Cubital Vein</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">The median cubital vein is the workhorse of routine blood draws for several reasons: it sits in the antecubital fossa where the bicipital aponeurosis protects deeper structures (brachial artery and median nerve) from a misdirected needle; it is large and superficial; and it is anchored by its connections to both the cephalic and basilic veins so it does not roll under the needle. The cephalic vein is the second choice. The basilic vein is the third because the medial antebrachial cutaneous nerve and median nerve sit close by, increasing the risk of nerve injury.</div>
</div>
</article>
<article class="plate" id="plate-12">
  <header class="plate-header">
    <div class="plate-num">Plate 12</div>
    <h3 class="plate-title">Superficial Veins of the Arm (Cadaveric)</h3>
    <p class="plate-desc">A cadaveric view of the superficial venous network of the arm, the same vessels you can see and palpate on a living patient when looking for a vein to access.</p>
  </header>
  <div class="plate-image"><img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Superficial Veins of the Arm (Cadaveric)" loading="lazy"></div>
  <div class="structures-heading">Identify These Structures</div><div class="id-cards"><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Axillary Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Visible at the proximal arm; receives the cephalic and basilic veins along with the deep brachial veins.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Cephalic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Travels up the lateral (radial) side of the arm. Visible just under the skin in lean individuals. Ascends to the deltopectoral groove before diving deep to join the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Basilic Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Travels up the medial (ulnar) side of the arm. Pierces the deep fascia approximately midway up the arm and joins the brachial veins to form the axillary vein.</div></div><div class="id-card"><div class="id-card-name">Median Cubital Vein</div><div class="id-card-text">Crosses the antecubital fossa connecting cephalic and basilic veins. Variable in pattern (some patients have an "M" shape with median antebrachial joining), but always the most reliable target for venipuncture.</div></div></div>
  <div class="pearl">
  <div class="pearl-label">Clinical Pearl</div>
  <div class="pearl-title">Finding a Vein in Real Life</div>
  <div class="pearl-text">When veins are hard to see (obesity, dehydration, dark skin tone, scarring from prior IV use), several maneuvers help: warm the limb (vasodilation), apply a tourniquet about 4 inches above the target site (engorges the vein), have the patient pump the fist (skeletal muscle pump fills veins), let the arm dangle (gravity), and use a transilluminator or ultrasound. Avoid sites with valves (visible as small bumps) because they make threading difficult. The dorsal venous network of the hand is a reliable backup site when the antecubital area is not accessible.</div>
</div>
</article>
</main>
